me":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, Danish, and Norwegian: topographic name for someone who lived in or by a small wood, from Middle English, Middle Low German, Danish, and Norwegian <i>holt</i>, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word. In England, the surname is widely distributed, but more common in Lancashire and Yorkshire than elsewhere."],"variants":[{"name":"Hohlt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Ordell.","North German: variant of   Holt   with the additional <i>h</i> reflecting the lengthened vowel or a variant of   Hohl   with the addition of excrescent <i>-t</i>.","Scandinavian: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holten","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Nils.","Dutch (also <b>Van Holten</b>) and North German: habitational name from any of the places so called, from Low German <i>holt</i> ‘holt, copse, small wood’. There are two in the Dutch province of Overijssel and another near Oberhausen in the Rhineland.","Danish: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holtan","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads so named, from the definite plural form of <i>holt</i> ‘small wood’ (see   Holt  )."]},{"name":"Holter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Selmer, Hilmar, Knute, Lars.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads in southeastern Norway, from the indefinite plural of <i>holt</i> ‘holt, small wood’ (see   Holt  ).","North German (also <b>Hölter</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places in Westphalia called Hölt and Holt (see   Holt  ). Compare   Hoelter  ."]},{"name":"Holtman","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Holt   + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","Americanized form of German   Holtmann  ."]},{"name":"Holtmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Udo, Aloys, Hans, Heinz.","North German: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorg, Erik, Helmer, Hjalmer, Knute, Nels, Nordahl, Selmer, Swen, Thorvald.","North German: variant of   Holt  .","North German: habitational name from any of several places so named."]},{"name":"Hoult","meanings":["English: variant of   Holt  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Holt was born about 1370, in Newton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Peter Holt, was 22 and his mother, Mrs. Anne Holt, was 21. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Joan De Holt. He died about 1433, at the age of 65."},"et":{"abt. 1370–abt. 1433":"umbes 1370–umbes 1433","1370–1433":"1370–1433","1372–1439":"1372–1439","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Sur